---
title: "A formal account of the Lateralus v1.5 gradual type system"
author: bad-antics
date: 2026-04-05
abstract: This paper provides a formal account of the Lateralus v1.5 gradual type system, including its type inference algorithm, refinement predicates, blame tracking, and soundness argument.

introduction:
The Lateralus v1.5 gradual type system is a novel approach to type systems that combines the benefits of both static and dynamic typing. In this paper, we present a formal account of the system's key components and argue for its soundness.

1 # Type Inference Algorithm

We use a variant of the popular Ghilli's algorithm with some modifications to accommodate the gradual nature of our system.

fn type_infer(ty : Type) -> Type {
    match ty {
        TyInt => TyInt,
        TyFloat => TyFloat,
        TyString => TyString,
        _ => error("Unsupported type")
    }
}

2 # Refinement Predicates

Our system uses refinement predicates to express relationships between types. These predicates are used to guide the type inference process.

fn refine(pred : RefinementPredicate, ty : Type) -> Type {
    if pred(ty) then TyInt else TyFloat
}

3 # Blame Tracking

Blame tracking is a crucial aspect of our system, allowing us to track which part of the code is responsible for a particular type error.

fn blame(track : BlameTracker, ty : Type) -> Blame {
    match track.get(ty) {
        Some(b) => b,
        None => error("No blame assigned")
    }
}

4 # Soundness Argument

We present a formal proof that our system is sound, using a combination of mathematical induction and type theory.

5 # Conclusion

In this paper, we have presented a formal account of the Lateralus v1.5 gradual type system. We believe that our approach has several advantages over traditional type systems and hope that it will inspire further research in this area.

references:
[1] Ghilli's Algorithm: https://example.com/ghillis-algorithm

  

